|title=Mahakashyapa's Smile: Language, Silence, and Mysticism |journal=Synthesis Philosophica |date=January 2014 |volume=58 |issue=2 |pages=387\u2013402 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/292087649 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217191449/https://www.researchgate.net/publication/292087649_Mahakashyapa's_Smile_Language_Silence_and_Mysticism |archive-date=17 February 2020 |url-status=live}}\n* {{Citation |last=Welter |first=A. |year=2000 |chapter=Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa\u2019s Smile: Silent Transmission and the Kung-an (K\u014dan) Tradition |title=The K\u014dan: Texts and Contexts in Zen Buddhism |pages=75\u2013109 |editor1-last=Heine |editor1-first=S. |editor2-last=Wright |editor2-first=D.S. |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=978-0-19-802780-5}}\n* {{Citation |first=A. |last=Welter |editor1-last=Buswell|editor1-first=Robert E.|title=Lineage |encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Buddhism|date=2004|publisher=Macmillan Reference USA, [[Thomson Gale]]|volume=2 |pages=462\u2013463 <!-- |isbn=0-02-865720-9-->|isbn=978-0-02-865718-9}}\n* {{Citation |last1=Wilson |first1=L. |editor-last1=Holt |editor-first1=J. |editor-last2=Kinnard |editor-first2=J.N. |editor-last3=Walters |editor-first3=J.S. |year=2003 |chapter=Beggars Can Be Choosers: Mah\u0101kassapa as a Selective Eater of Offerings |title=Constituting Communities, Therav\u0101da Buddhism and the Religious Cultures of South and Southeast Asia |pages=57\u201370 |isbn=978-0-7914-8705-1}}\n* {{Citation |last1=Witanachchi |first1=C.|editor1-last=Malalasekera |editor1-first=G. P. |editor2-last=Weeraratne |editor2-first=W. G. |editor1-link=G. P. Malalasekera |title=\u0100nanda |encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia of Buddhism |date=1965 |publisher=[[Government of Sri Lanka]] |url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/231090852/Enceylopaedia-of-Buddhism-Vol-i |volume=1 |oclc=2863845613}}\n* {{Citation |last1=Zurcher |first1=Erik |editor1-last=Williams |editor1-first=Paul |title=Buddhism: Critical Concepts in Religious Studies, 8: Buddhism in China, East Asia, and Japan |date=2005 |publisher=[[Routledge]] |chapter=Buddhist Influence on Early Taoism |isbn=0-415-33234-6 |page=378}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.accesstoinsight.org/lib/authors/hecker/wheel345.html Mah\u0101 Kassapa, Father of the Sangha], by Hellmuth Hecker, biography based on the [[Pali Canon|P\u0101li Canon]], revised and enlarged translation from Wissen und Wandel volume XXI, number 6, 1975, (German) by [[Nyanaponika]] Thera, The Wheel Publication No. 345, {{ISBN|955-24-0026-0}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20190713140808/https://www.accesstoinsight.org/lib/authors/hecker/wheel345.html archived here.]\n* [https://www.learnreligions.com/disciple-mahakasyapa-father-of-sangha-449645 ''Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa''], hosted by Learning Religion, [https://web.archive.org/web/20200217191247/https://www.learnreligions.com/disciple-mahakasyapa-father-of-sangha-449645 archived here.]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-rel|bu}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Lineage (Buddhism)|Lineage of Buddhist patriarchs]]<br /><small>(According to the [[Zen]] schools of China and Japan)</small>|before=[[Gautama Buddha|\u015a\u0101kyamuni]]<br /><small>Beginning of the lineage</small>|after=[[Ananda]]|years=}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Buddhism topics}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mahakasyapa}}\n[[Category:Foremost disciples of Gautama Buddha]]\n[[Category:Arhats]]\n[[Category:Indian Buddhist monks]]\n[[Category:Buddhist patriarchs]]\n[[Category:5th-century Buddhist monks]]\n", "name_user": "Vami IV", "label": "safe", "comment": "ce: rmv errant \"a\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mah%C4%81k%C4%81%C5%9Byapa"}
{"title_page": "Kleptomania", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Kleptomania (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Kleptomania\n| synonyms        = Klopemania<ref>{{cite web|url=http://phrontistery.info/mania.html|title=Word List: Definitions of Mania Words and Obsessions|website=phrontistery.info}}</ref>\n| image           = Klepto-shoe-400-247.gif\n| alt             = \n| caption         = The result of kleptomania\n| pronounce       = \n| field           = [[Psychiatry]]\n| width           = \n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n\n'''Kleptomania''' is the inability to resist the urge to [[stealing|steal]] items, usually for reasons other than personal use or financial gain. First described in 1816, kleptomania is classified in [[psychiatry]] as an [[impulse control disorder]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Shulman|first=Terrence Daryl|title=Something for Nothing: Shoplifting Addiction & Recovery|year=2004|publisher=Infinity Publishing|location=Haverford, PA|isbn=0741417790|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QN92oESUXfwC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> Some of the main characteristics of the disorder suggest that kleptomania could be an [[obsessive-compulsive spectrum]] disorder, but also share similarities with addictive and mood disorders.<ref>''Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders'' IV. pp. 1211.</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Grant|first=Jon|date=2006|title=Understanding and Treating Kleptomania: New Models and New Treatments|journal=The Israel Journal of Psychiatry and Related Sciences|volume=43|issue=2|pages=81\u20137|pmid=16910369|id={{ProQuest|236926707}}}}</ref>\n\nThe disorder is frequently under-diagnosed and is regularly associated with other psychiatric disorders, particularly [[anxiety disorder|anxiety]] and [[eating disorders]], and [[alcoholism|alcohol]] and [[substance abuse]]. Patients with kleptomania are typically treated with therapies in other areas due to the [[Comorbidity|comorbid]] grievances rather than issues directly related to kleptomania.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Grant | first1 = JE | year = 2004 | title = Co-occurrence of personality disorders in persons with kleptomania: a preliminary investigation | url = | journal = Journal of the American Academy of Psychiatry and the Law | volume = 32 | issue = 4| pages = 395\u20138 | pmid = 15704625 }}</ref>\n\nOver the last 100 years, a shift from [[Psychotherapy|psychotherapeutic]] to [[Psychopharmacology|psychopharmacological]] interventions for kleptomania has occurred. [[Pharmacology|Pharmacological]] treatments using [[selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors]] (SSRIs), [[mood stabilizer]]s and [[Opioid antagonist|opioid receptor antagonists]], and other [[antidepressant]]s along with [[cognitive behavioral therapy]], have yielded positive results.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Aizer | first1 = A. | last2 = Lowengrub | first2 = K. | last3 = Dannon | first3 = P.N. | year = 2004 | title = Kleptomania after head trauma: two case reports and the combination treatment strategies | url = | journal = Clinical Neuropharmacology | volume = 27 | issue = 5| pages = 211\u20135 | pmid = 15602100 | doi=10.1097/01.wnf.0000144042.66342.d3}}</ref> However, there have also been reports of kleptomania induced by selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kindler|first=Seth|last2=Dannon|first2=Pinhas N.|last3=Iancu|first3=Iulian|last4=Sasson|first4=Yehuda|last5=Zohar|first5=Joseph|date=1997-04-01|title=Emergence of Kleptomania During Treatment for Depression with Serotonin Selective Reuptake Inhibitors|journal=Clinical Neuropharmacology|language=ENGLISH|volume=20|issue=2|pages=126\u2013129|doi=10.1097/00002826-199704000-00003|pmid=9099464|issn=0362-5664}}</ref> Nowadays, children are mostly seen to be affected by kleptomania.\n\n== Signs and symptoms ==\nSome of the fundamental components of kleptomania include recurring intrusive thoughts, impotence to resist the compulsion to engage in stealing, and the release of internal pressure following the act. These symptoms suggest that kleptomania could be regarded as an obsessive-compulsive type of disorder.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = G\u00fcrlek Y\u00fcksel | first1 = E. | last2 = Ta\u015fkin | first2 = E.O. | last3 = Yilmaz Ovali | first3 = G. | last4 = Kara\u00e7am | first4 = M. | last5 = Esen Danaci | first5 = A. | year = 2007 | title = Case report: kleptomania and other psychiatric symptoms after carbon monoxide intoxication |language=Turkish|journal=T\u00fcrk Psikiyatri Dergisi (Turkish Journal of Psychiatry) | url = | volume = 18 | issue = 1| pages = 80\u20136 | pmid = 17364271 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Grant | first1 = J.E. | year = 2006 | title = Understanding and treating kleptomania: new models and new treatments | url = | journal = The Israel Journal of Psychiatry and Related Sciences | volume = 43 | issue = 2| pages = 81\u20137 | pmid = 16910369 }}</ref>\n\nPeople diagnosed with kleptomania often have other types of disorders involving mood, anxiety, eating, impulse control, and drug use. They also have great levels of [[Stress (psychological)|stress]], [[guilt (emotion)|guilt]], and [[remorse]], and privacy issues accompanying the act of stealing. These signs are considered to either cause or intensify general comorbid disorders. The characteristics of the behaviors associated with stealing could result in other problems as well, which include social segregation and substance abuse. The many types of other disorders frequently occurring along with kleptomania usually make clinical diagnosis uncertain.<ref>Hollander, Eric; Stein, Dan (2006). [https://books.google.com/books?id=u2wVP8KJJtcC&pg=PA223 ''Clinical Manual of Impulse-Control Disorders'']. 1st ed. Arlington: American Psyschiatric Publishing Inc. p. 223-4.</ref>\n\nThere is a difference between ordinary theft and kleptomania: \"ordinary theft (whether planned or impulsive) is deliberate and is motivated by the usefulness of the object or its monetary worth,\" whereas with kleptomania, there \"is the recurrent failure to resist impulses to steal items even though the items are not needed for personal use or for their monetary value.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=DSM-IV-TR|year=2000|publisher=American Psychiatric Association|location=Arlinton, VA|pages=667\u2013668|edition=4th|editor=American Psychiatric Association}}</ref>\n\n== Cause ==\n=== Psychoanalytic models ===\nMany psychoanalytic theorists suggest that kleptomania is a person's attempt \"to obtain symbolic compensation for an actual or anticipated loss\", and feel that the key to understanding its etiology lies in the symbolic meaning of the stolen items.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Cupchik |first1=W. |last2=Atcheson |first2=D.J. |title=Shoplifting: An Occasional Crime Of The Moral Majority |journal=The Bulletin of the American Academy of Psychiatry and the Law |year=1983 |volume=11 |issue=4 |pages=343\u201354|pmid=6661563 }}</ref> [[Drive theory]] was used to propose that the act of stealing is a defense mechanism which serves as to modulate or keep undesirable feelings or emotions from being expressed.<ref name=Goldman1991/> Some French psychiatrists suggest that kleptomaniacs may just want the item that they steal and the feeling they get from  theft itself.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fullerton|first=Ronald A.|date=2016-08-11|title=Psychoanalyzing kleptomania|journal=Marketing Theory|volume=7|issue=4|pages=335\u2013352|language=en|doi=10.1177/1470593107083160}}</ref>\n\n=== Cognitive-behavioral models ===\nCognitive-behavioral models have been replacing psychoanalytic models in describing the development of kleptomania. Cognitive-behavioral practitioners often conceptualize the disorders as being the result of [[operant conditioning]], [[Chaining|behavioral chaining]], distorted cognitions, and poor coping mechanisms.<ref>Gauthier & Pellerin, 1982.</ref><ref>Kohn & Antonuccio, 2002.</ref> Cognitive-behavioral models suggest that the behavior is [[reinforcement|positively reinforced]] after the person steals some items. If this individual experiences minimal or no negative consequences (punishment), then the likelihood that the behavior will reoccur is increased. As the behavior continues to occur, stronger antecedents or cues become contingently linked with it, in what ultimately becomes a powerful behavioral chain. According to cognitive-behavioral theory (CBT), both antecedents and consequences may either be in the environment or cognitions. For example, Kohn and Antonuccio (2002) describe a client\u2019s antecedent cognitions, which include thoughts such as \"I\u2019m smarter than others and can get away with it\"; \"they deserve it\"; \"I want to prove to myself that I can do it\"; and \"my family deserves to have better things\". These thoughts were strong cues to stealing behaviors. All of these thoughts were precipitated by additional antecedents which were thoughts about family, financial, and work stressors or feelings of depression. \"Maintaining\" cognitions provided additional reinforcement for stealing behaviors and included feelings of vindication and pride, for example: \"score one for the 'little guy' against the big corporations\". Although those thoughts were often afterward accompanied by feelings of remorse, this came too late in the operant sequence to serve as a viable punisher. Eventually, individuals with kleptomania come to rely upon stealing as a way of coping with stressful situations and distressing feelings, which serve to further maintain the behavior and decrease the number of available alternative coping strategies.<ref>{{cite book|last1=John|first1=C.S. |author2=Kalal, D. M. |author3=Kastell, K. |author4=Viera, J. |title=Practitioner's guide to evidence-based psychotherapy|chapter=Kleptomania |editor1-first=J. E. |editor1-last=Fisher |editor2-first=W. T.| editor2-last=O'Donohue |year=2006 |publisher=Springer |location=New York}}</ref>\n\n=== Biological models ===\nBiological models explaining the origins of kleptomania have been based mostly on pharmacotherapy treatment studies that used selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs), mood stabilizers, and opioid receptor antagonists.<ref name=GrantKim2002/><ref name=\"Dannon2001\"/>\n\nSome studies using SSRIs have observed that opioid antagonists appear to reduce the urge to steal and mute the \"rush\" typically experienced immediately after stealing by some subjects suffering from kleptomania. This would suggest that poor regulation of [[serotonin]], [[dopamine]], and/or natural opioids within the brain are to blame for kleptomania, linking it with impulse control and affective disorders.<ref name=Goldman1991/><ref name=GrantKim2002/><ref name=Dannon2001/>\n\nAn alternative explanation too based on opioid antagonist studies states that kleptomania is similar to the \"self-medication\" model, in which stealing stimulates the person\u2019s natural opioid system. \"The opioid release 'soothes' the patients, treats their sadness, or reduces their anxiety. Thus, stealing is a mechanism to relieve oneself from a chronic state of hyperarousal, perhaps produced by prior stressful or traumatic events, and thereby modulate affective states.\"<ref name=GrantKim2002/>{{rp|354}}\n\n== Diagnosis ==\nDisagreement surrounds the method by which kleptomania is considered and diagnosed. On one hand, some researchers believe that kleptomania is merely theft and dispute the suggestion that there are psychological mechanisms involved, while others observe kleptomania as part of a substance-related addiction. Yet others categorize kleptomania as a variation of an impulse control disorder, such as [[obsessive-compulsive disorder]] or eating disorders.<ref name=GrantKim2002>{{cite journal | last1 = Grant | first1 = J.E. | last2 = Kim | first2 = S.W. | year = 2002 | title = Clinical characteristics and associated psychopathology of 22 patients with kleptomania | url = | journal = Comprehensive Psychiatry | volume = 43 | issue = | page = 5 | doi = 10.1053/comp.2002.34628 | pmid = 12216013 }}</ref>{{rp|378\u201384}}\n\nAccording to the ''[[Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders]]'' fourth edition (DSM IV-TR), a frequent and widely used guide for the diagnosis of mental disorders, the following symptoms and characteristics are the diagnostic criteria for kleptomania:\n#  repeated inability to defend against urges to steal things that are not essential for private use or for their economic value;\n#  escalating sense of pressure immediately prior to performing the theft;\n#  satisfaction, fulfillment or relief at the point of performing the theft;\n#  the theft is not executed to convey antagonism or revenge, and is not in reaction to a delusion or a fantasy; and\n#  the thieving is not better accounted for by behavior disorder, a manic episode, or antisocial personality disorder.<ref name=PrestaMarazziti>{{cite journal | last1 = Presta | first1 = S. | last2 = Marazziti | first2 = D. | last3 = Dell'Osso | first3 = L. | last4 = Pfanner | first4 = C. | last5 = Pallanti | first5 = S. | last6 = Cassano | first6 = G.B. | year = 2002 | title = Kleptomania: clinical features and comorbidity in an Italian sample | url = | journal = Comprehensive Psychiatry | volume = 43 | issue = 1| pages = 7\u201312 | doi = 10.1053/comp.2002.29851 | pmid = 11788913 }}</ref>\n\nSkeptics have decried kleptomania as an invalid psychiatric concept exploited in legal defenses of wealthy female shoplifters. During the twentieth century, kleptomania was strongly linked with the increased prevalence of department stores, and \"department store kleptomaniacs\" were a widely held social stereotype that had political implications.<ref name=McElroyPope>{{cite journal | last1 = McElroy | first1 = S.L. | last2 = Pope | first2 = H.G. | last3 = Hudson | first3 = J.I. | last4 = Keck | first4 = P.E. | last5 = White | first5 = K.L. | year = 1991 | title = Kleptomania: a report of 20 cases | url = | journal = The American Journal of Psychiatry | volume = 148 | issue = 5| pages = 652\u20137 | pmid = 2018170 | doi=10.1176/ajp.148.5.652}}</ref>\n\n== Comorbidity ==\nKleptomania seems to be linked with other psychiatric disorders, especially mood swings, anxiety, eating disorders, and alcohol and substance abuse. The occurrence of stealing as a behavior in conjunction with eating disorders, particularly [[bulimia nervosa]], is frequently taken as a sign of the harshness of the eating disorder.<ref name=BayleCaci>{{cite journal | last1 = Bayl\u00e9 | first1 = F.J. | last2 = Caci | first2 = H. | last3 = Millet | first3 = B. | last4 = Richa | first4 = S. | last5 = Oli\u00e9 | first5 = J.P. | year = 2003 | title = Psychopathology and comorbidity of psychiatric disorders in patients with kleptomania | url = | journal = The American Journal of Psychiatry | volume = 160 | issue = 8| pages = 1509\u201313 | doi = 10.1176/appi.ajp.160.8.1509 | pmid = 12900315 }}</ref>\n\nA likely connection between depression and kleptomania was reported as early as 1911. It has since been extensively established in clinical observations and available case reports. The mood disorder could come first or co-occur with the beginning of kleptomania. In advanced cases, depression may result in self-inflicted injury and could even lead to suicide. Some people have reported relief from depression or manic symptoms after theft.<ref name=GrantCompPsych>{{cite journal | last1 = Grant | first1 = J.E. | year = 2003 | title = Family history and psychiatric comorbidity in persons with kleptomania | url = | journal = Comprehensive Psychiatry | volume = 44 | issue = 6| pages = 437\u201341 | doi = 10.1016/S0010-440X(03)00150-0 | pmid = 14610719 }}</ref>\n\nIt has been suggested that because kleptomania is linked to strong compulsive and impulsive qualities, it can be viewed as a variation of obsessive-compulsive spectrum disorders, together with [[pathological gambling]], [[compulsive buying]], [[pyromania]], [[nailbiting]] and [[trichotillomania]]. This point achieves support from the unusually higher cases of obsessive-compulsive disorder (OCD; see [[#Obsessive-compulsive disorder|below]]) in close relatives of patients with kleptomania.<ref name=MatsungaKiriike>{{cite journal | last1 = Matsunaga | first1 = H. | last2 = Kiriike | first2 = N. | last3 = Matsui | first3 = T. | last4 = Oya | first4 = K. | last5 = Okino | first5 = K. | last6 = Stein | first6 = D.J. | year = 2005 | title = Impulsive disorders in Japanese adult patients with obsessive-compulsive disorder | url = | journal = Comprehensive Psychiatry | volume = 46 | issue = 1| pages = 43\u20139 | doi = 10.1016/j.comppsych.2004.07.001 | pmid = 15714194 }}</ref>\n\n=== Substance abuse disorder ===\nKleptomania and drug addictions seem to have central qualities in common, including:\n* recurring or compulsive participation in a behavior in spite of undesirable penalties;\n* weakened control over the disturbing behavior;\n* a need or desire condition before taking part in the problematic behavior; and\n* a positive pleasure-seeking condition throughout the act of the disturbing behavior.\nData from epidemiological studies additionally propose that there is an affiliation between kleptomania and substance use disorders along with high rates in a unidirectional manner. Phenomenological data maintain that there is a relationship between kleptomania and drug addictions. A higher percentage of cases of kleptomania has been noted in adolescents and young adults, and a lesser number of cases among older adults, which imply an analogous natural history to that seen in substance use disorders. Family history data also propose a probable common genetic input to alcohol use and kleptomania. Substance use disorders are more common in kin of persons with kleptomania than in the general population. Furthermore, pharmacological data (e.g., the probable efficacy of the opioid antagonist, [[naltrexone]], in the treatment of both kleptomania and substance use disorders) could present additional support for a joint relationship between kleptomania and substance use disorders. Based on the idea that kleptomania and substance use disorders may share some etiological features, it could be concluded that kleptomania would react optimistically to the same treatments. As a matter of fact, certain nonmedical treatment methods that are successful in treating substance abuse are also accommodating in treating kleptomania.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Grant|first1=J.E.|last2=Grant|first2=M.P.H. |last3=Odlaug|first3=Brian L.|last4=Kim |first4=S.W.|title=Kleptomania: Clinical Characteristics and Relationship to Substance Use Disorders|journal=The American Journal of Drug and Alcohol Abuse|year=2010|volume=36|pages=291\u2013295|doi=10.3109/00952991003721100|pmid=20575650|issue=5}}</ref>\n\n=== Obsessive-compulsive disorder ===<!-- An earlier section links here. Please do not change. -->\nKleptomania is frequently thought of as being a part of [[obsessive-compulsive disorder]] (OCD), since the irresistible and uncontrollable actions are similar to the frequently excessive, unnecessary, and unwanted rituals of OCD. Some individuals with kleptomania demonstrate hoarding symptoms that resemble those with OCD.\nPrevalence rates between the two disorders do not demonstrate a strong relationship. Studies examining the comorbidity of OCD in subjects with kleptomania have inconsistent results, with some showing a relatively high co-occurrence (45%-60%)<ref name=PrestaMarazziti/><ref name=McElroyPope/> while others demonstrate low rates (0%-6.5%).<ref name=BayleCaci/><ref name=GrantCompPsych/> Similarly, when rates of kleptomania have been examined in subjects with OCD, a relatively low co-occurrence was found (2.2%-5.9%).<ref name=MatsungaKiriike/><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Fontenelle | first1 = L.F. | last2 = Mendlowicz | first2 = M.V. | last3 = Versiani | first3 = M. | year = 2005 | title = Impulse control disorders in patients with obsessive-compulsive disorder | url = | journal = Psychiatry and Clinical Neurosciences | volume = 59 | issue = 1| pages = 30\u201337 | doi=10.1111/j.1440-1819.2005.01328.x | pmid=15679537}}</ref>\n\n=== Pyromania ===\n[[Pyromania]], another impulse disorder, has many ties to kleptomania. Many pyromaniacs begin fires alongside petty stealing which often appears similar to kleptomania.<ref>{{Cite book | url = https://books.google.com/?id=ubG51n2NgfwC&pg=PA365#v=onepage&q=pyromania&f=false | title = Kaplan and Sadock's Concise Textbook of Clinical Psychiatry | isbn = 9780781787468 | last1 = Sadock | first1 = Benjamin J | last2 = Sadock | first2 = Virginia A | date = 21 April 2008}}</ref>\n\n== Treatment ==\nAlthough the disorder has been known to psychologists for a long time, the cause of kleptomania is still ambiguous. Therefore, a diverse range of therapeutic approaches have been introduced for its treatment. These treatments include: psychoanalytic oriented psychotherapy, behavioral therapy, and pharmacotherapy.<ref name=Dannon2001/>\n\n=== Psychoanalytic and psychodynamic approach ===\nSeveral explanations of the mechanics of kleptomania have been presented. A contemporary social approach proposes that kleptomania is an outcome of consumerism and the large quantity of commodities in society. [[Psychodynamic]] theories depend on a variety of points of view in defining the disorder. [[Psychoanalytic theory|Psychoanalysts]] define the condition as an indication of a defense mechanism deriving in the unconscious ego against anxiety, prohibited intuition or desires, unsettled struggle or forbidden sexual drives, dread of castration, sexual excitement, and sexual fulfillment and orgasm throughout the act of stealing.<ref>\"From stack-firing to pyromania: medico-legal concepts of insane arson in British, US and European contexts, c. 1800-1913\". Part I. ''History of Psychiatry''. 2010; '''21''': 243-260</ref> The psychoanalytic and psycho-dynamic approach to kleptomania granted the basis for prolonged psychoanalytic or psycho-dynamic [[psychotherapy]] as the core treatment method for a number of years. Like most psychiatric conditions, kleptomania was observed within the psycho-dynamic lens instead of being viewed as a bio-medical disorder. However, the prevalence of psychoanalytic approach contributed to the growth of other approaches, particularly in the biological domain.<ref>Levy, Sidney (2007). \"Challenging the Philosophical Assumptions of Marketing\". ''Journal of Macro-marketing''. 27: 7-14.</ref>\n\n=== Behavioral and cognitive intervention ===\n[[Cognitive-behavioural therapy]] (CBT) has primarily substituted the psychoanalytic and dynamic approach in the treatment of kleptomania. Numerous behavioural approaches have been recommended as helpful according to several cases stated in the literature. They include: hidden sensitisation by unpleasant images of nausea and vomiting, [[aversion therapy]] (for example, aversive holding of breath to achieve a slightly painful feeling every time a desire to steal or the act is imagined), and [[systematic desensitisation]].<ref>\"Historical Research in the Journal of Macromarketing, 1981-2005\". ''Journal of Macromarketing''. 2006; '''26''': 178-192.</ref> In certain instances, the use of combining several methods such as hidden sensitisation along with exposure and response prevention were applied. Even though the approaches used in CBT need more research and investigation in kleptomania, success in combining these methods with medication was illustrated over the use of drug treatment as the single method of treatment.<ref>\"Introduction to the Special Issue on the History of Marketing Thought\". ''Marketing Theory''. September 1, 2005. '''5''': 235-237.</ref>\n\n=== Drug treatment ===\nThe phenomenological similarity and the suggested common basic biological dynamics of kleptomania and OCD, pathological gambling and trichotillomania gave rise to the theory that the similar groups of medications could be used in all these conditions. Consequently, the primary use of [[selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor]] (SSRI) group, which is a form of antidepressant, has been used in kleptomania and other impulse control disorders such as binge eating and OCD. [[Electroconvulsive therapy]] (ECT), [[lithium pharmacology|lithium]] and [[valproic acid]] (sodium valproate) have been used as well.<ref>\"Consumer Misbehavior: The Rise of Self-Service Grocery Retailing and Shoplifting in the United Kingdom c. 1950-1970\". ''Journal of Macromarketing''. June 1, 2005. '''25''': 66-75.</ref>\n\nThe SSRI's usage is due to the assumption that the biological dynamics of these conditions derives from low levels of [[serotonin]] in brain synapses, and that the efficacy of this type of therapy will be relevant to kleptomania and to other comorbid conditions.<ref>\"Sources of Immoderation and Proportion in Marketing\". ''Thought Marketing Theory''. June 1, 2005. '''5''': 221-231.</ref>\n\n[[Opioid receptor antagonist]]s are regarded as practical in lessening urge-related symptoms, which is a central part of impulse control disorders; for this reason, they are used in treatment of substance abuse. This quality makes them helpful in treating kleptomania and impulse control disorders in general. The most frequently used drug is [[naltrexone]], a long-acting competitive antagonist. Naltrexone acts mainly at [[\u03bc-opioid receptor|\u03bc-receptors]], but also antagonises [[\u03ba-opioid receptor|\u03ba-]] and \u03bb-receptors.<ref>{{cite journal| last1=Fullerton |first1=Ronald A. |last2=Punj |first2=Girish N. |date=June 2004 |journal=Journal of Macromarketing |volume=24 |issue=1 |doi=10.1177/0276146704263811 |title=Shoplifting as Moral Insanity: Historical Perspectives on Kleptomania |pages=8\u201316}}</ref>\n\nThere have been no controlled studies of the psycho-pharmacological treatment of kleptomania. This could be as a consequence of kleptomania being a rare phenomenon and the difficulty in achieving a large enough sample. Facts about this issue come largely from case reports or from bits and pieces gathered from a comparatively small number of cases enclosed in a group series.<ref name=Dannon2001>{{cite journal|last1=Durst|first1=Rimona|last2=Katz |first2=Gregory |last3=Teitelbaum |first3=Josef Zislin |last4=Dannon |first4=N.P.|title=Kleptomania: Diagnosis and Treatment Options|journal=CNS Drugs|year=2001|volume=15|issue=3|pages=185\u2013195|doi=10.2165/00023210-200115030-00003|pmid=11463127}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nIn the nineteenth century, French psychiatrists began to observe kleptomaniacal behavior, but were constrained by their approach.{{Citation needed|date=September 2012}} By 1890, a large body of case material on kleptomania had been developed. [[Hysteria]], imbecility, cerebral defect, and [[menopause]] were advanced as theories to explain these seemingly nonsensical behaviors, and many linked kleptomania to immaturity, given the inclination of young children to take whatever they want. These French and German observations later became central to psychoanalytic explanations of kleptomania.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Juqueller |first1=Paul |first2=Jean |last2=Vinchon |title=Revue de Psychiatrie et de Psychologies Experimental |journal=L'Historie de la Kleptomanie |year=1914|pages=47\u201364}}</ref>\n\n=== Etymology ===\nThe term ''kleptomania'' was derived from the [[Greek language|Greek]] words ''[[wikt:\u03ba\u03bb\u03ad\u03c0\u03c4\u03c9#Ancient Greek|\u03ba\u03bb\u03ad\u03c0\u03c4\u03c9]]'' (klepto) \"to steal\" and ''[[wikt:\u03bc\u03b1\u03bd\u03af\u03b1#Ancient Greek|\u03bc\u03b1\u03bd\u03af\u03b1]]'' (mania) \"mad desire, compulsion\". Its meaning roughly corresponds to \"compulsion to steal\" or \"compulsive stealing\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2009/04/090401101900.htm|title=Drug Suppresses The Compulsion To Steal, Study Shows}}</ref>\n\n=== First generation of psychoanalysis ===\nIn the early twentieth century, kleptomania was viewed more as a legal excuse for self-indulgent haut bourgeois ladies than a valid psychiatric aliment by French psychiatrists.<ref>{{cite journal|last=A.|first=Antheaume|title=L'Enc\u00e9phale|journal=La L\u00e9gende de la Kleptomanie Affection Mental Fictive|year=1925|volume=20|pages=368\u2013388}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|first1=Max|last1=Friedemann|last2=Willard |first2=Clara (trans.)|title=Psychoanalytical Review |journal=Cleptomanis: The Analytic and Forensic Aspects |year=1930 |volume=17 |pages=452\u2013470}}</ref>\n\n[[Sigmund Freud]], the creator of controversial [[psychoanalytic theory]], believed that the underlying dynamics of human behaviours associated with uncivilized savages\u2014impulses were curbed by inhibitions for social life. He did not believe human behaviour to be rational. He created a large theoretical corpus which his disciples applied to such psychological problems as kleptomania. In 1924, one of his followers, [[Wilhelm Stekel]], read the case of a female kleptomaniac who was driven by suppressed sexual urges to take hold of \"something forbidden, secretly\". Stekel concluded that kleptomania was \"suppressed and superseded sexual desire carried out through medium of a symbol or symbolic action. Every compulsion in psychic life is brought about by suppression\".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Wilhelm |first1=Stekel |last2=Teslaar |first2=James S. Van (trans.) |title=Sexual root of kleptomania |journal=Peculiarities of Behaviour |year=1924 |volume=2 |series=2 |issue=Journal of the American Institute of Criminal Law and Criminology |pages=239\u2013246}}</ref>\n\n=== Second generation of psychoanalysis ===\n[[Fritz Wittels]] argued that kleptomaniacs were sexually underdeveloped people who felt deprived of love and had little experience with human sexual relationships; stealing was their sex life, giving them thrills so powerful that they did not want to be cured. Male kleptomaniacs, in his view, were homosexual or invariably effeminate.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Fritz |first=Wittels |authorlink=Fritz Wittels|journal=Kleptomania and Other Psychopathology |year=1942 |volume=4 |series=2 |pages=205\u2013216}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Wittels |first=Fritz |authorlink=Fritz Wittels|title=Some remarks on kleptomania |year=1929 |volume=29 |issue=3 |series=3 |journal=The Journal of Nervous and Mental Disease |pages=241\u2013251| doi = 10.1097/00005053-192903000-00001 }}</ref>\n\nA famous large-scale analysis of shoplifters in the United Kingdom ridiculed Stekel's notion of sexual symbolism and claimed that one out of five apprehended shoplifters was a \"psychiatric\".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gibbens |first1=T.C.N. |first2=Joyce |last2=Prince |title=Shoplifting |year=1961 |journal=London: The Institute for the Study and Treatment of Delinquency}}</ref>\n\n=== New perspectives ===\nEmpirically based conceptual articles have argued that kleptomania is becoming more common than previously thought, and occurs more frequently among women than men.  These ideas are new in recent history but echo those current in the mid to late nineteenth century.<ref name=Goldman1991>{{cite journal|last=Goldman|first=Marcus J. |title=Kleptomania: Making Sense of the Nonsensical |journal=American Journal of Psychiatry |year=1991 |volume=148 |pmid=1853988|issue=8 |pages=986\u201396 |doi=10.1176/ajp.148.8.986}}</ref>{{rp|986\u2013996}}\n\n== Society and culture ==\nStealing frequently becomes an obsession. Although people know they could get caught and marked for life, they find it hard to give up the habit. Major symptoms include a person's decreased resistance to steal objects unnecessarily, feeling entitled to own them at any cost. If a person gets away with stealing they may experience an adrenaline rush and for some successful thefts, dopamine is produced by the brain that can affect heart rate and blood pressure.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://law.jrank.org/pages/12004/Causes-Crime.html|title=Causes of Crime - Explaining Crime, Physical Abnormalities, Psychological Disorders, Social And Economic Factors, Broken Windows, Income And Education|website=law.jrank.org}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n<!-- * [[Animo furandi]]/[[Animus furandi]] -->\n* ''[[Portrait of a Kleptomaniac]]''\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n| DiseasesDB      = \n| ICD10           = {{ICD10|F|63|2|f|60}}\n| ICD9            = {{ICD9|312.32}}\n| ICDO            = \n| OMIM            = \n| MedlinePlus     = \n| eMedicineSubj   = \n| eMedicineTopic  = \n| MeshID          = D007174\n| GeneReviewsName = \n| SNOMED CT       = 69361009\n}}\n{{Commons category-inline}}\n\n{{Mental and behavioural disorders|selected = adult}}\n\n[[Category:Habit and impulse disorders]]\n[[Category:Abnormal psychology]]\n[[Category:Psychiatric diagnosis]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Kleptomania (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Kleptomania\n| synonyms        = Klopemania<ref>{{cite web|url=http://phrontistery.info/mania.html|title=Word List: Definitions of Mania Words and Obsessions|website=phrontistery.info}}</ref>\n| image           = Klepto-shoe-400-247.gif\n| alt             = \n| caption         = The result of kleptomania\n| pronounce       = \n| field           = [[Psychiatry]]\n| width           = \n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n\n'''Kleptomania''' is the inability to resist the urge to [[stealing|steal]] items, usually for reasons other than personal use or financial gain. First described in 1816, kleptomania is classified in [[psychiatry]] as an [[impulse control disorder]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Shulman|first=Terrence Daryl|title=Something for Nothing: Shoplifting Addiction & Recovery|year=2004|publisher=Infinity Publishing|location=Haverford, PA|isbn=0741417790|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QN92oESUXfwC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> Some of the main characteristics of the disorder suggest that kleptomania could be an [[obsessive-compulsive spectrum]] disorder, but also share similarities with addictive and mood disorders.<ref>''Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders'' IV. pp. 1211.</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Grant|first=Jon|date=2006|title=Understanding and Treating Kleptomania: New Models and New Treatments|journal=The Israel Journal of Psychiatry and Related Sciences|volume=43|issue=2|pages=81\u20137|pmid=16910369|id={{ProQuest|236926707}}}}</ref>\n\nThe disorder is frequently under-diagnosed and is regularly associated with other psychiatric disorders, particularly [[anxiety disorder|anxiety]] and [[eating disorders]], and [[alcoholism|alcohol]] and [[substance abuse]]. Patients with kleptomania are typically treated with therapies in other areas due to the [[Comorbidity|comorbid]] grievances rather than issues directly related to kleptomania.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Grant | first1 = JE | year = 2004 | title = Co-occurrence of personality disorders in persons with kleptomania: a preliminary investigation | url = | journal = Journal of the American Academy of Psychiatry and the Law | volume = 32 | issue = 4| pages = 395\u20138 | pmid = 15704625 }}</ref>\n\nOver the last 100 years, a shift from [[Psychotherapy|psychotherapeutic]] to [[Psychopharmacology|psychopharmacological]] interventions for kleptomania has occurred. [[Pharmacology|Pharmacological]] treatments using [[selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors]] (SSRIs), [[mood stabilizer]]s and [[Opioid antagonist|opioid receptor antagonists]], and other [[antidepressant]]s along with [[cognitive behavioral therapy]], have yielded positive results.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Aizer | first1 = A. | last2 = Lowengrub | first2 = K. | last3 = Dannon | first3 = P.N. | year = 2004 | title = Kleptomania after head trauma: two case reports and the combination treatment strategies | url = | journal = Clinical Neuropharmacology | volume = 27 | issue = 5| pages = 211\u20135 | pmid = 15602100 | doi=10.1097/01.wnf.0000144042.66342.d3}}</ref> However, there have also been reports of kleptomania induced by selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kindler|first=Seth|last2=Dannon|first2=Pinhas N.|last3=Iancu|first3=Iulian|last4=Sasson|first4=Yehuda|last5=Zohar|first5=Joseph|date=1997-04-01|title=Emergence of Kleptomania During Treatment for Depression with Serotonin Selective Reuptake Inhibitors|journal=Clinical Neuropharmacology|language=ENGLISH|volume=20|issue=2|pages=126\u2013129|doi=10.1097/00002826-199704000-00003|pmid=9099464|issn=0362-5664}}</ref> Nowadays, children are mostly seen to be affected by kleptomania.\n\n== Signs and symptoms ==\nSome of the fundamental components of kleptomania include recurring intrusive thoughts, impotence to resist the compulsion to engage in stealing, and the release of internal pressure following the act. These symptoms suggest that kleptomania could be regarded as an obsessive-compulsive type of disorder.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = G\u00fcrlek Y\u00fcksel | first1 = E. | last2 = Ta\u015fkin | first2 = E.O. | last3 = Yilmaz Ovali | first3 = G. | last4 = Kara\u00e7am | first4 = M. | last5 = Esen Danaci | first5 = A. | year = 2007 | title = Case report: kleptomania and other psychiatric symptoms after carbon monoxide intoxication |language=Turkish|journal=T\u00fcrk Psikiyatri Dergisi (Turkish Journal of Psychiatry) | url = | volume = 18 | issue = 1| pages = 80\u20136 | pmid = 17364271 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Grant | first1 = J.E. | year = 2006 | title = Understanding and treating kleptomania: new models and new treatments | url = | journal = The Israel Journal of Psychiatry and Related Sciences | volume = 43 | issue = 2| pages = 81\u20137 | pmid = 16910369 }}</ref>\n\nPeople diagnosed with kleptomania often have other types of disorders involving mood, anxiety, eating, impulse control, and drug use. They also have great levels of [[Stress (psychological)|stress]], [[guilt (emotion)|guilt]], and [[remorse]], and privacy issues accompanying the act of stealing. These signs are considered to either cause or intensify general comorbid disorders. The characteristics of the behaviors associated with stealing could result in other problems as well, which include social segregation and substance abuse. The many types of other disorders frequently occurring along with kleptomania usually make clinical diagnosis uncertain.<ref>Hollander, Eric; Stein, Dan (2006). [https://books.google.com/books?id=u2wVP8KJJtcC&pg=PA223 ''Clinical Manual of Impulse-Control Disorders'']. 1st ed. Arlington: American Psyschiatric Publishing Inc. p. 223-4.</ref>\n\nThere is a difference between ordinary theft and kleptomania: \"ordinary theft (whether planned or impulsive) is deliberate and is motivated by the usefulness of the object or its monetary worth,\" whereas with kleptomania, there \"is the recurrent failure to resist impulses to steal items even though the items are not needed for personal use or for their monetary value.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=DSM-IV-TR|year=2000|publisher=American Psychiatric Association|location=Arlinton, VA|pages=667\u2013668|edition=4th|editor=American Psychiatric Association}}</ref>\n\n== Cause ==\n=== Psychoanalytic models ===\nMany psychoanalytic theorists suggest that kleptomania is a person's attempt \"to obtain symbolic compensation for an actual or anticipated loss\", and feel that the key to understanding its etiology lies in the symbolic meaning of the stolen items.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Cupchik |first1=W. |last2=Atcheson |first2=D.J. |title=Shoplifting: An Occasional Crime Of The Moral Majority |journal=The Bulletin of the American Academy of Psychiatry and the Law |year=1983 |volume=11 |issue=4 |pages=343\u201354|pmid=6661563 }}</ref> [[Drive theory]] was used to propose that the act of stealing is a defense mechanism which serves as to modulate or keep undesirable feelings or emotions from being expressed.<ref name=Goldman1991/> Some French psychiatrists suggest that kleptomaniacs may just want the item that they steal and the feeling they get from  theft itself.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fullerton|first=Ronald A.|date=2016-08-11|title=Psychoanalyzing kleptomania|journal=Marketing Theory|volume=7|issue=4|pages=335\u2013352|language=en|doi=10.1177/1470593107083160}}</ref>\n\n=== Cognitive-behavioral models ===\nCognitive-behavioral models have been replacing psychoanalytic models in describing the development of kleptomania. Cognitive-behavioral practitioners often conceptualize the disorders as being the result of [[operant conditioning]], [[Chaining|behavioral chaining]], distorted cognitions, and poor coping mechanisms.<ref>Gauthier & Pellerin, 1982.</ref><ref>Kohn & Antonuccio, 2002.</ref> Cognitive-behavioral models suggest that the behavior is [[reinforcement|positively reinforced]] after the person steals some items. If this individual experiences minimal or no negative consequences (punishment), then the likelihood that the behavior will reoccur is increased. As the behavior continues to occur, stronger antecedents or cues become contingently linked with it, in what ultimately becomes a powerful behavioral chain. According to cognitive-behavioral theory (CBT), both antecedents and consequences may either be in the environment or cognitions. For example, Kohn and Antonuccio (2002) describe a client\u2019s antecedent cognitions, which include thoughts such as \"I\u2019m smarter than others and can get away with it\"; \"they deserve it\"; \"I want to prove to myself that I can do it\"; and \"my family deserves to have better things\". These thoughts were strong cues to stealing behaviors. All of these thoughts were precipitated by additional antecedents which were thoughts about family, financial, and work stressors or feelings of depression. \"Maintaining\" cognitions provided additional reinforcement for stealing behaviors and included feelings of vindication and pride, for example: \"score one for the 'little guy' against the big corporations\". Although those thoughts were often afterward accompanied by feelings of remorse, this came too late in the operant sequence to serve as a viable punisher. Eventually, individuals with kleptomania come to rely upon stealing as a way of coping with stressful situations and distressing feelings, which serve to further maintain the behavior and decrease the number of available alternative coping strategies.<ref>{{cite book|last1=John|first1=C.S. |author2=Kalal, D. M. |author3=Kastell, K. |author4=Viera, J. |title=Practitioner's guide to evidence-based psychotherapy|chapter=Kleptomania |editor1-first=J. E. |editor1-last=Fisher |editor2-first=W. T.| editor2-last=O'Donohue |year=2006 |publisher=Springer |location=New York}}</ref>\n\n=== Biological models ===\nBiological models explaining the origins of kleptomania have been based mostly on pharmacotherapy treatment studies that used selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs), mood stabilizers, and opioid receptor antagonists.<ref name=GrantKim2002/><ref name=\"Dannon2001\"/>\n\nSome studies using SSRIs have observed that opioid antagonists appear to reduce the urge to steal and mute the \"rush\" typically experienced immediately after stealing by some subjects suffering from kleptomania. This would suggest that poor regulation of [[serotonin]], [[dopamine]], and/or natural opioids within the brain are to blame for kleptomania, linking it with impulse control and affective disorders.<ref name=Goldman1991/><ref name=GrantKim2002/><ref name=Dannon2001/>\n\nAn alternative explanation too based on opioid antagonist studies states that kleptomania is similar to the \"self-medication\" model, in which stealing stimulates the person\u2019s natural opioid system. \"The opioid release 'soothes' the patients, treats their sadness, or reduces their anxiety. Thus, stealing is a mechanism to relieve oneself from a chronic state of hyperarousal, perhaps produced by prior stressful or traumatic events, and thereby modulate affective states.\"<ref name=GrantKim2002/>{{rp|354}}\n\n== Diagnosis ==\nDisagreement surrounds the method by which kleptomania is considered and diagnosed. On one hand, some researchers believe that kleptomania is merely theft and dispute the suggestion that there are psychological mechanisms involved, while others observe kleptomania as part of a substance-related addiction. Yet others categorize kleptomania as a variation of an impulse control disorder, such as [[obsessive-compulsive disorder]] or eating disorders.<ref name=GrantKim2002>Grant, J.E.; Kim, S.W. (2002). \"Clinical characteristics and associated psychopathology of 22 patients with kleptomania\". ''Comprehensive Psychiatry''. '''43'''(5). [[doi:10.1053/comp.2002.34628]]. {{PMID|12216013}}.</ref>{{rp|378\u201384}}\n\nAccording to the ''[[Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders]]'' fourth edition (DSM IV-TR), a frequent and widely used guide for the diagnosis of mental disorders, the following symptoms and characteristics are the diagnostic criteria for kleptomania:\n#  repeated inability to defend against urges to steal things that are not essential for private use or for their economic value;\n#  escalating sense of pressure immediately prior to performing the theft;\n#  satisfaction, fulfillment or relief at the point of performing the theft;\n#  the theft is not executed to convey antagonism or revenge, and is not in reaction to a delusion or a fantasy; and\n#  the thieving is not better accounted for by behavior disorder, a manic episode, or antisocial personality disorder.<ref name=PrestaMarazziti>{{cite journal | last1 = Presta | first1 = S. | last2 = Marazziti | first2 = D. | last3 = Dell'Osso | first3 = L. | last4 = Pfanner | first4 = C. | last5 = Pallanti | first5 = S. | last6 = Cassano | first6 = G.B. | year = 2002 | title = Kleptomania: clinical features and comorbidity in an Italian sample | url = | journal = Comprehensive Psychiatry | volume = 43 | issue = 1| pages = 7\u201312 | doi = 10.1053/comp.2002.29851 | pmid = 11788913 }}</ref>\n\nSkeptics have decried kleptomania as an invalid psychiatric concept exploited in legal defenses of wealthy female shoplifters. During the twentieth century, kleptomania was strongly linked with the increased prevalence of department stores, and \"department store kleptomaniacs\" were a widely held social stereotype that had political implications.<ref name=McElroyPope>{{cite journal | last1 = McElroy | first1 = S.L. | last2 = Pope | first2 = H.G. | last3 = Hudson | first3 = J.I. | last4 = Keck | first4 = P.E. | last5 = White | first5 = K.L. | year = 1991 | title = Kleptomania: a report of 20 cases | url = | journal = The American Journal of Psychiatry | volume = 148 | issue = 5| pages = 652\u20137 | pmid = 2018170 | doi=10.1176/ajp.148.5.652}}</ref>\n\n== Comorbidity ==\nKleptomania seems to be linked with other psychiatric disorders, especially mood swings, anxiety, eating disorders, and alcohol and substance abuse. The occurrence of stealing as a behavior in conjunction with eating disorders, particularly [[bulimia nervosa]], is frequently taken as a sign of the harshness of the eating disorder.<ref name=BayleCaci>Bayl\u00e9, F.J.; Caci, H.; Millet, B.; Richa, S.; Oli\u00e9, J.P. (2003). \"Psychopathology and comorbidity of psychiatric disorders in patients with kleptomania\". ''The American Journal of Psychiatry''. '''160'''(8): 1509\u201313. [[doi:10.1176/appi.ajp.160.8.1509]]. {{PMID|12900315}}.</ref>\n\nA likely connection between depression and kleptomania was reported as early as 1911. It has since been extensively established in clinical observations and available case reports. The mood disorder could come first or co-occur with the beginning of kleptomania. In advanced cases, depression may result in self-inflicted injury and could even lead to suicide. Some people have reported relief from depression or manic symptoms after theft.<ref name=GrantCompPsych>Grant, J.E. (2003). \"Family history and psychiatric comorbidity in persons with kleptomania\". ''Comprehensive Psychiatry''. '''44'''(6): 437\u201341. [[doi:10.1016/S0010-440X(03)00150-0]]. {{PMID|14610719}}.</ref>\n\nIt has been suggested that because kleptomania is linked to strong compulsive and impulsive qualities, it can be viewed as a variation of obsessive-compulsive spectrum disorders, together with [[pathological gambling]], [[compulsive buying]], [[pyromania]], [[nailbiting]] and [[trichotillomania]]. This point achieves support from the unusually higher cases of obsessive-compulsive disorder (OCD; see [[#Obsessive-compulsive disorder|below]]) in close relatives of patients with kleptomania.<ref name=MatsungaKiriike>Matsunaga, H.; Kiriike, N.; Matsui, T.; Oya, K.; Okino, K.; Stein, D.J. (2005). \"Impulsive disorders in Japanese adult patients with obsessive-compulsive disorder\". ''Comprehensive Psychiatry''. '''46'''(1): 43\u20139. [[doi:10.1016/j.comppsych.2004.07.001]]. {{PMID|15714194}}.</ref>\n\n=== Substance abuse disorder ===\nKleptomania and drug addictions seem to have central qualities in common, including:\n* recurring or compulsive participation in a behavior in spite of undesirable penalties;\n* weakened control over the disturbing behavior;\n* a need or desire condition before taking part in the problematic behavior; and\n* a positive pleasure-seeking condition throughout the act of the disturbing behavior.\nData from epidemiological studies additionally propose that there is an affiliation between kleptomania and substance use disorders along with high rates in a unidirectional manner. Phenomenological data maintain that there is a relationship between kleptomania and drug addictions. A higher percentage of cases of kleptomania has been noted in adolescents and young adults, and a lesser number of cases among older adults, which imply an analogous natural history to that seen in substance use disorders. Family history data also propose a probable common genetic input to alcohol use and kleptomania. Substance use disorders are more common in kin of persons with kleptomania than in the general population. Furthermore, pharmacological data (e.g., the probable efficacy of the opioid antagonist, [[naltrexone]], in the treatment of both kleptomania and substance use disorders) could present additional support for a joint relationship between kleptomania and substance use disorders. Based on the idea that kleptomania and substance use disorders may share some etiological features, it could be concluded that kleptomania would react optimistically to the same treatments. As a matter of fact, certain nonmedical treatment methods that are successful in treating substance abuse are also accommodating in treating kleptomania.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Grant|first1=J.E.|last2=Grant|first2=M.P.H. |last3=Odlaug|first3=Brian L.|last4=Kim |first4=S.W.|title=Kleptomania: Clinical Characteristics and Relationship to Substance Use Disorders|journal=The American Journal of Drug and Alcohol Abuse|year=2010|volume=36|pages=291\u2013295|doi=10.3109/00952991003721100|pmid=20575650|issue=5}}</ref>\n\n=== Obsessive-compulsive disorder ===<!-- An earlier section links here. Please do not change. -->\nKleptomania is frequently thought of as being a part of [[obsessive-compulsive disorder]] (OCD), since the irresistible and uncontrollable actions are similar to the frequently excessive, unnecessary, and unwanted rituals of OCD. Some individuals with kleptomania demonstrate hoarding symptoms that resemble those with OCD.\nPrevalence rates between the two disorders do not demonstrate a strong relationship. Studies examining the comorbidity of OCD in subjects with kleptomania have inconsistent results, with some showing a relatively high co-occurrence (45%-60%)<ref name=PrestaMarazziti/><ref name=McElroyPope/> while others demonstrate low rates (0%-6.5%).<ref name=BayleCaci/><ref name=GrantCompPsych/> Similarly, when rates of kleptomania have been examined in subjects with OCD, a relatively low co-occurrence was found (2.2%-5.9%).<ref name=MatsungaKiriike/><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Fontenelle | first1 = L.F. | last2 = Mendlowicz | first2 = M.V. | last3 = Versiani | first3 = M. | year = 2005 | title = Impulse control disorders in patients with obsessive-compulsive disorder | url = | journal = Psychiatry and Clinical Neurosciences | volume = 59 | issue = 1| pages = 30\u201337 | doi=10.1111/j.1440-1819.2005.01328.x | pmid=15679537}}</ref>\n\n=== Pyromania ===\n[[Pyromania]], another impulse disorder, has many ties to kleptomania. Many pyromaniacs begin fires alongside petty stealing which often appears similar to kleptomania.<ref>{{Cite book | url = https://books.google.com/?id=ubG51n2NgfwC&pg=PA365#v=onepage&q=pyromania&f=false | title = Kaplan and Sadock's Concise Textbook of Clinical Psychiatry | isbn = 9780781787468 | last1 = Sadock | first1 = Benjamin J | last2 = Sadock | first2 = Virginia A | date = 21 April 2008}}</ref>\n\n== Treatment ==\nAlthough the disorder has been known to psychologists for a long time, the cause of kleptomania is still ambiguous. Therefore, a diverse range of therapeutic approaches have been introduced for its treatment. These treatments include: psychoanalytic oriented psychotherapy, behavioral therapy, and pharmacotherapy.<ref name=Dannon2001/>\n\n=== Psychoanalytic and psychodynamic approach ===\nSeveral explanations of the mechanics of kleptomania have been presented. A contemporary social approach proposes that kleptomania is an outcome of consumerism and the large quantity of commodities in society. [[Psychodynamic]] theories depend on a variety of points of view in defining the disorder. [[Psychoanalytic theory|Psychoanalysts]] define the condition as an indication of a defense mechanism deriving in the unconscious ego against anxiety, prohibited intuition or desires, unsettled struggle or forbidden sexual drives, dread of castration, sexual excitement, and sexual fulfillment and orgasm throughout the act of stealing.<ref>\"From stack-firing to pyromania: medico-legal concepts of insane arson in British, US and European contexts, c. 1800-1913\". Part I. ''History of Psychiatry''. September 1, 2010. '''21''': 243-260</ref> The psychoanalytic and psycho-dynamic approach to kleptomania granted the basis for prolonged psychoanalytic or psycho-dynamic [[psychotherapy]] as the core treatment method for a number of years. Like most psychiatric conditions, kleptomania was observed within the psycho-dynamic lens instead of being viewed as a bio-medical disorder. However, the prevalence of psychoanalytic approach contributed to the growth of other approaches, particularly in the biological domain.<ref>Levy, Sidney (March 1, 2007). \"Challenging the Philosophical Assumptions of Marketing\". ''Journal of Macro-marketing''. '''27''': 7-14.</ref>\n\n=== Behavioral and cognitive intervention ===\n[[Cognitive-behavioural therapy]] (CBT) has primarily substituted the psychoanalytic and dynamic approach in the treatment of kleptomania. Numerous behavioural approaches have been recommended as helpful according to several cases stated in the literature. They include: hidden sensitisation by unpleasant images of nausea and vomiting, [[aversion therapy]] (for example, aversive holding of breath to achieve a slightly painful feeling every time a desire to steal or the act is imagined), and [[systematic desensitisation]].<ref>\"Historical Research in the Journal of Macromarketing, 1981-2005\". ''Journal of Macromarketing''. December 1, 2006. '''26''': 178-192.</ref> In certain instances, the use of combining several methods such as hidden sensitisation along with exposure and response prevention were applied. Even though the approaches used in CBT need more research and investigation in kleptomania, success in combining these methods with medication was illustrated over the use of drug treatment as the single method of treatment.<ref>\"Introduction to the Special Issue on the History of Marketing Thought\". ''Marketing Theory''. September 1, 2005. '''5''': 235-237.</ref>\n\n=== Drug treatment ===\nThe phenomenological similarity and the suggested common basic biological dynamics of kleptomania and OCD, pathological gambling and trichotillomania gave rise to the theory that the similar groups of medications could be used in all these conditions. Consequently, the primary use of [[selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor]] (SSRI) group, which is a form of antidepressant, has been used in kleptomania and other impulse control disorders such as binge eating and OCD. [[Electroconvulsive therapy]] (ECT), [[lithium pharmacology|lithium]] and [[valproic acid]] (sodium valproate) have been used as well.<ref>\"Consumer Misbehavior: The Rise of Self-Service Grocery Retailing and Shoplifting in the United Kingdom c. 1950-1970\". ''Journal of Macromarketing''. June 1, 2005. '''25''': 66-75.</ref>\n\nThe SSRI's usage is due to the assumption that the biological dynamics of these conditions derives from low levels of [[serotonin]] in brain synapses, and that the efficacy of this type of therapy will be relevant to kleptomania and to other comorbid conditions.<ref>\"Sources of Immoderation and Proportion in Marketing\". ''Thought Marketing Theory''. June 1, 2005. '''5''': 221-231.</ref>\n\n[[Opioid receptor antagonist]]s are regarded as practical in lessening urge-related symptoms, which is a central part of impulse control disorders; for this reason, they are used in treatment of substance abuse. This quality makes them helpful in treating kleptomania and impulse control disorders in general. The most frequently used drug is [[naltrexone]], a long-acting competitive antagonist. Naltrexone acts mainly at [[\u03bc-opioid receptor|\u03bc-receptors]], but also antagonises [[\u03ba-opioid receptor|\u03ba-]] and \u03bb-receptors.<ref>{{cite journal| last1=Fullerton |first1=Ronald A. |last2=Punj |first2=Girish N. |date=June 2004 |journal=Journal of Macromarketing |volume=24 |issue=1 |doi=10.1177/0276146704263811 |title=Shoplifting as Moral Insanity: Historical Perspectives on Kleptomania |pages=8\u201316}}</ref>\n\nThere have been no controlled studies of the psycho-pharmacological treatment of kleptomania. This could be as a consequence of kleptomania being a rare phenomenon and the difficulty in achieving a large enough sample. Facts about this issue come largely from case reports or from bits and pieces gathered from a comparatively small number of cases enclosed in a group series.<ref name=Dannon2001>{{cite journal|last1=Durst|first1=Rimona|last2=Katz |first2=Gregory |last3=Teitelbaum |first3=Josef Zislin |last4=Dannon |first4=N.P.|title=Kleptomania: Diagnosis and Treatment Options|journal=CNS Drugs|year=2001|volume=15|issue=3|pages=185\u2013195|doi=10.2165/00023210-200115030-00003|pmid=11463127}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nIn the nineteenth century, French psychiatrists began to observe kleptomaniacal behavior, but were constrained by their approach.{{Citation needed|date=September 2012}} By 1890, a large body of case material on kleptomania had been developed. [[Hysteria]], imbecility, cerebral defect, and [[menopause]] were advanced as theories to explain these seemingly nonsensical behaviors, and many linked kleptomania to immaturity, given the inclination of young children to take whatever they want. These French and German observations later became central to psychoanalytic explanations of kleptomania.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Juqueller |first1=Paul |first2=Jean |last2=Vinchon |title=Revue de Psychiatrie et de Psychologies Experimental |journal=L'Historie de la Kleptomanie |year=1914|pages=47\u201364}}</ref>\n\n=== Etymology ===\nThe term ''kleptomania'' was derived from the [[Greek language|Greek]] words ''[[wikt:\u03ba\u03bb\u03ad\u03c0\u03c4\u03c9#Ancient Greek|\u03ba\u03bb\u03ad\u03c0\u03c4\u03c9]]'' (klepto) \"to steal\" and ''[[wikt:\u03bc\u03b1\u03bd\u03af\u03b1#Ancient Greek|\u03bc\u03b1\u03bd\u03af\u03b1]]'' (mania) \"mad desire, compulsion\". Its meaning roughly corresponds to \"compulsion to steal\" or \"compulsive stealing\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2009/04/090401101900.htm|title=Drug Suppresses The Compulsion To Steal, Study Shows}}</ref>\n\n=== First generation of psychoanalysis ===\nIn the early twentieth century, kleptomania was viewed more as a legal excuse for self-indulgent haut bourgeois ladies than a valid psychiatric aliment by French psychiatrists.<ref>{{cite journal|last=A.|first=Antheaume|title=L'Enc\u00e9phale|journal=La L\u00e9gende de la Kleptomanie Affection Mental Fictive|year=1925|volume=20|pages=368\u2013388}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|first1=Max|last1=Friedemann|last2=Willard |first2=Clara (trans.)|title=Psychoanalytical Review |journal=Cleptomanis: The Analytic and Forensic Aspects |year=1930 |volume=17 |pages=452\u2013470}}</ref>\n\n[[Sigmund Freud]], the creator of controversial [[psychoanalytic theory]], believed that the underlying dynamics of human behaviours associated with uncivilized savages\u2014impulses were curbed by inhibitions for social life. He did not believe human behaviour to be rational. He created a large theoretical corpus which his disciples applied to such psychological problems as kleptomania. In 1924, one of his followers, [[Wilhelm Stekel]], read the case of a female kleptomaniac who was driven by suppressed sexual urges to take hold of \"something forbidden, secretly\". Stekel concluded that kleptomania was \"suppressed and superseded sexual desire carried out through medium of a symbol or symbolic action. Every compulsion in psychic life is brought about by suppression\".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Wilhelm |first1=Stekel |last2=Teslaar |first2=James S. Van (trans.) |title=Sexual root of kleptomania |journal=Peculiarities of Behaviour |year=1924 |volume=2 |series=2 |issue=Journal of the American Institute of Criminal Law and Criminology |pages=239\u2013246}}</ref>\n\n=== Second generation of psychoanalysis ===\n[[Fritz Wittels]] argued that kleptomaniacs were sexually underdeveloped people who felt deprived of love and had little experience with human sexual relationships; stealing was their sex life, giving them thrills so powerful that they did not want to be cured. Male kleptomaniacs, in his view, were homosexual or invariably effeminate.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Fritz |first=Wittels |authorlink=Fritz Wittels|journal=Kleptomania and Other Psychopathology |year=1942 |volume=4 |series=2 |pages=205\u2013216}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Wittels |first=Fritz |authorlink=Fritz Wittels|title=Some remarks on kleptomania |year=1929 |volume=29 |issue=3 |series=3 |journal=The Journal of Nervous and Mental Disease |pages=241\u2013251| doi = 10.1097/00005053-192903000-00001 }}</ref>\n\nA famous large-scale analysis of shoplifters in the United Kingdom ridiculed Stekel's notion of sexual symbolism and claimed that one out of five apprehended shoplifters was a \"psychiatric\".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gibbens |first1=T.C.N. |first2=Joyce |last2=Prince |title=Shoplifting |year=1961 |journal=London: The Institute for the Study and Treatment of Delinquency}}</ref>\n\n=== New perspectives ===\nEmpirically based conceptual articles have argued that kleptomania is becoming more common than previously thought, and occurs more frequently among women than men.  These ideas are new in recent history but echo those current in the mid to late nineteenth century.<ref name=Goldman1991>{{cite journal|last=Goldman|first=Marcus J. |title=Kleptomania: Making Sense of the Nonsensical |journal=American Journal of Psychiatry |year=1991 |volume=148 |pmid=1853988|issue=8 |pages=986\u201396 |doi=10.1176/ajp.148.8.986}}</ref>{{rp|986\u2013996}}\n\n== Society and culture ==\nStealing frequently becomes an obsession. Although people know they could get caught and marked for life, they find it hard to give up the habit. Major symptoms include a person's decreased resistance to steal objects unnecessarily, feeling entitled to own them at any cost. If a person gets away with stealing they may experience an adrenaline rush and for some successful thefts, dopamine is produced by the brain that can affect heart rate and blood pressure.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://law.jrank.org/pages/12004/Causes-Crime.html|title=Causes of Crime - Explaining Crime, Physical Abnormalities, Psychological Disorders, Social And Economic Factors, Broken Windows, Income And Education|website=law.jrank.org}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n<!-- * [[Animo furandi]]/[[Animus furandi]] -->\n* ''[[Portrait of a Kleptomaniac]]''\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n| DiseasesDB      = \n| ICD10           = {{ICD10|F|63|2|f|60}}\n| ICD9            = {{ICD9|312.32}}\n| ICDO            = \n| OMIM            = \n| MedlinePlus     = \n| eMedicineSubj   = \n| eMedicineTopic  = \n| MeshID          = D007174\n| GeneReviewsName = \n| SNOMED CT       = 69361009\n}}\n{{Commons category-inline}}\n\n{{Mental and behavioural disorders|selected = adult}}\n\n[[Category:Habit and impulse disorders]]\n[[Category:Abnormal psychology]]\n[[Category:Psychiatric diagnosis]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Journal cites:,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kleptomania"}
{"title_page": "Olivia DeJonge", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Olivia de Jonge\n| image         = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|df=y|1998|04|30}}\n| birth_place   = [[Melbourne]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], Australia\n| residence     = [[Melbourne]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]\n| nationality   = Australian\n| occupation    = Actress\n| years_active  = 2011\u2013present\n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Olivia de Jonge''' ({{IPAc-en|d|\u0259|\u02c8|j|\u0252|\u014b}};<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FUW1JtH8yI8|title=Will: ASIDES - An Educated Women (Ep. 2)|publisher=TNT|date=10 July 2017|accessdate=17 December 2018}}</ref> born 30 April 1998) is an Australian actress, known for playing Tara Swift / Shaneen Quigg in the series ''[[Hiding (TV series)|Hiding]]'', Becca in the film ''[[The Visit (2015 American film)|The Visit]]'' and Elle in [[Netflix]] series ''[[The Society (TV series)|The Society]]''.\n\n== Early life ==\nDeJonge was born in 1998 in [[Melbourne, Victoria]], the daughter of Robyn and Rob DeJonge, a businessman. She moved to [[Perth, Western Australia]] with her parents at the age of five, where she grew up in [[Peppermint Grove, Western Australia|Peppermint Grove]]. She has studied at the [[Presbyterian Ladies' College, Perth|Presbyterian Ladies' College]], Perth.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.perthnow.com.au/entertainment/confidential/perth-schoolgirl-olivia-dejonge-on-her-hollywood-movie-the-visit/news-story/a7598fe1f32ca58d5cc8ef9f9a82fca8?sv=10b7b9a2e8076e151155e8f4c6ae0049|title=Perth schoolgirl Olivia DeJonge on her Hollywood movie The Visit|last=Caccetta|first=Wendy|date=23 August 2015|work=Perth Now|publisher=Sunday Times|access-date=30 July 2016|via=}}</ref><ref name=\"Aug2015Yahoo\" />\n\n== Career ==\nIn 2014, DeJonge made her feature film debut in the film ''[[The Sisterhood of Night]]''; she starred along with [[Georgie Henley]], [[Kara Hayward]], and [[Kal Penn]].<ref name=\"Aug2015Yahoo\" /> [[Caryn Waechter]] directed the film, which was released on 10 April 2015, after getting a premiere in October 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Scheck|first1=Frank|title='The Sisterhood of Night': Film Review|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/movie/sisterhood-night/review/787508|accessdate=10 September 2015|work=hollywoodreporter.com|date=9 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, DeJonge appeared in the [[ABC (Australian TV channel)|Australian ABC]]'s television drama series ''[[Hiding (TV series)|Hiding]]'', on which she played one of the lead roles as Tara Swift / Shaneen Quigg.<ref name=\"Aug2015Yahoo\" /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Yeap|first1=Sue|title=No hiding place for successful Olivia|url=https://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/entertainment/a/26205273/no-hiding-place-for-successful-olivia/|accessdate=10 September 2015|work=yahoo.com|date=5 February 2015}}</ref> She played the co-lead role of Becca in the horror film ''[[The Visit (2015 American film)|The Visit]]'', along with [[Ed Oxenbould]].<ref name=\"Aug2015Yahoo\" /><ref name=Aug2015Yahoo>{{cite news|last1=McRae|first1=Ross|title=School can wait for Perth starlet|url=https://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/wa/a/29321894/school-can-wait-for-perth-starlet/|accessdate=10 September 2015|work=yahoo.com|date=22 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925162251/https://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/wa/a/29321894/school-can-wait-for-perth-starlet/|archive-date=25 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[M. Night Shyamalan]] directed the film, which had its premiere on 31 August 2015, and was released on 11 September 2015 by [[Universal Pictures]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The Visit (2015)|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=blumhouse2015.htm|publisher=boxofficemojo.com|accessdate=10 September 2015}}</ref> In 2017, DeJonge starred as Alice Burbage in the [[TNT (U.S. TV network)|TNT]] series, ''[[Will (TV series)|Will]]''.\n\nIn October 2019, it was announced that DeJonge will star alongside  as [[Priscilla Presley]] in [[Baz Luhrmann]]\u2019s upcoming [[Elvis Presley]] biopic.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McNary|first1=Dave|title=Baz Luhrmann's Elvis Biopic Casts 'The Society's' Olivia DeJonge as Priscilla Presley|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/baz-luhrmann-elvis-movie-priscilla-presley-olivia-dejonge-1203383589/ |accessdate=4 November 2019|work=variety.com|date=25 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''Good Pretender''\n| Ally\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''Polarised''\n| Beth\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''Eleven Thirty''\n| Sally\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[The Sisterhood of Night]]''\n| Lavinia Hall\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[The Visit (2015 American film)|The Visit]]''\n| Becca\n| Nominee - [[42nd Saturn Awards]] [[Saturn Award for Best Performance by a Younger Actor|Best Performance by a Younger Actor]]\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Scare Campaign]]''\n| Abby\n| \n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Better Watch Out (film)|Better Watch Out]]''\n| Ashley\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''Undertow''\n|Angie\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''Love and Other Places''\n|Shaz\n|Short film\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Stray Dolls]]''\n| Dallas\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Josie & Jack]]''\n| Josie\n|\n|-\n| 2021\n| ''[[Elvis (2021 film)|Elvis]]''\n| [[Priscilla Presley]]\n| Filming\n|}\n\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Hiding (TV series)|Hiding]]''\n| Shaneen Quigg / Tara Swift\n| 8 episodes\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Will (TV series)|Will]]\n| Alice Burbage\n| 10 episodes\n|-\n| 2019\u2013present\n| ''[[The Society (TV series)|The Society]]''\n| Elle\n| Main role\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|4609822}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:DeJonge, Olivia}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Perth, Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Australian film actresses]]\n[[Category:Australian television actresses]]\n[[Category:Australian child actresses]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Olivia DeJonge\n| image         = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|df=y|1998|04|30}}\n| birth_place   = [[Melbourne]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], Australia\n| residence     = [[Melbourne]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]\n| nationality   = Australian\n| occupation    = Actress\n| years_active  = 2011\u2013present\n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Olivia DeJonge''' ({{IPAc-en|d|\u0259|\u02c8|j|\u0252|\u014b}};<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FUW1JtH8yI8|title=Will: ASIDES - An Educated Women (Ep. 2)|publisher=TNT|date=10 July 2017|accessdate=17 December 2018}}</ref> born 30 April 1998) is an Australian actress, known for playing Tara Swift / Shaneen Quigg in the series ''[[Hiding (TV series)|Hiding]]'', Becca in the film ''[[The Visit (2015 American film)|The Visit]]'' and Elle in [[Netflix]] series ''[[The Society (TV series)|The Society]]''.\n\n== Early life ==\nDeJonge was born in 1998 in [[Melbourne, Victoria]], the daughter of Robyn and Rob DeJonge, a businessman. She moved to [[Perth, Western Australia]] with her parents at the age of five, where she grew up in [[Peppermint Grove, Western Australia|Peppermint Grove]]. She has studied at the [[Presbyterian Ladies' College, Perth|Presbyterian Ladies' College]], Perth.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.perthnow.com.au/entertainment/confidential/perth-schoolgirl-olivia-dejonge-on-her-hollywood-movie-the-visit/news-story/a7598fe1f32ca58d5cc8ef9f9a82fca8?sv=10b7b9a2e8076e151155e8f4c6ae0049|t